President Obama has announced his intent to nominate three individuals to the Board of Directors of the Legal Services Corporation. The nominees are Sharon L. Browne, Charles Norman Wiltse Keckler, and Victor B. Maddox. 

Sharon L. Browne is a principal attorney in the Pacific Legal Foundation's Individual Rights Practice group. She has experience as a trial and appellate lawyer and has served as an adjunct professor of law. Browne's articles have been published in law reviews, and she has served on the California Advisory Committee to the United States Commission on Civil Rights.

Charles Norman Wiltse Keckler currently teaches civil procedure and evidence at Pennsylvania State University's Dickinson School of Law. He has worked at the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services Administration for Children and Families, where he focused on regulatory matters and oversaw federal grantees providing services to disadvantaged populations. Keckler has also taught law and worked as an appellate and trial litigator.

Victor B. Maddox has been practicing law for nearly 30 years, both in the public and private sectors. He is currently a partner at a law firm in Louisville, Kentucky, where he handles trial, arbitration, and appellate matters. Maddox has also worked as a Trial Attorney for the U.S. Department of Justice and as Counsel for the U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee. He has experience in commercial litigation, civil rights, intellectual property, and constitutional law.